  "texts": [
    "To address these concerns, it is crucial that both providers and patients have access to information about when algorithms are used in decisionmaking processes, as well as information on how those algorithms were developed and validated.",
    "Additionally, there must be accountability for the patient outcomes of these AI-driven decisions, with continuous monitoring and validation to ensure they do not perpetuate inequities in healthcare delivery.",
    "Currently, at many institutions, patients and clinicians cannot opt out of AI-driven quality improvement (QI) processes, research, or clinical care.",
    "AI vendors have not provided clear information on how they will establish safeguards to protect patient privacy and ensure that clinicians are fully aware of what data is being recorded about their actions, how this data is accessed, and how it may be linked to patient care or potential malpractice and legal claims.",
    "Additionally, they have not clarified how they will prevent the misuse of EHR data that could lead to unfair or inaccurate restrictions on services."
  ],
